ing -->\n\n<!-- wp:newspack-blocks/homepage-articles {\"className\":\"is-style-borders\",\"showExcerpt\":false,\"showDate\":false,\"showImage\":false,\"moreButtonText\":\"SEE MORE\",\"showAuthor\":false,\"postsToShow\":4,\"categories\":[\"14\"],\"typeScale\":2} /--></div></div>\n<!-- /wp:group -->\n\n<!-- wp:group {\"customBackgroundColor\":\"#f5f5f5\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-group has-background\" style=\"background-color:#f5f5f5\"><div class=\"wp-block-group__inner-container\"><!-- wp:heading {\"align\":\"center\",\"level\":5,\"textColor\":\"white\"} -->\n<h5 class=\"has-white-color has-text-color has-text-align-center\">SOME CONTENT</h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:newspack-blocks/homepage-articles {\"className\":\"is-style-borders\",\"showExcerpt\":false,\"showDate\":false,\"moreButtonText\":\"SEE MORE\",\"showAuthor\":false,\"postsToShow\":1,\"categories\":[\"22\"],\"typeScale\":2} /-->\n\n<!-- wp:newspack-blocks/homepage-articles {\"className\":\"is-style-borders\",\"showExcerpt\":false,\"showDate\":false,\"showImage\":false,\"moreButtonText\":\"SEE MORE\",\"showAuthor\":false,\"postsToShow\":4,\"categories\":[\"22\"],\"typeScale\":2} /--></div></div>\n<!-- /wp:group --></div>\n<!-- /wp:column --></div>\n<!-- /wp:columns -->\n\n<!-- wp:group {\"className\":\"newspack-pattern homepage-posts__style-5\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-group newspack-pattern homepage-posts__style-5\"><div class=\"wp-block-group__inner-container\"><!-- wp:columns {\"className\":\"is-style-default\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-columns is-style-default\"><!-- wp:column -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\"><!-- wp:newspack-blocks/homepage-articles {\"className\":\"is-style-borders\",\"showExcerpt\":false,\"showAvatar\":false,\"postsToShow\":1,\"categories\":[\"11\"],\"typeScale\":3,\"imageScale\":1,\"sectionHeader\":\"MYANMAR\"} /-->\n\n<!-- wp:newspack-blocks/homepage-articles {\"className\":\"is-style-borders\",\"showExcerpt\":false,\"showImage\":false,\"showAuthor\":false,\"showAvatar\":false,\"mediaPosition\":\"left\",\"categories\":[\"11\"],\"typeScale\":1,\"imageScale\":1} /--></div>\n<!-- /wp:column -->\n\n<!-- wp:column -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\"><!-- wp:newspack-blocks/homepage-articles {\"className\":\"is-style-borders\",\"showExcerpt\":false,\"showAvatar\":false,\"postsToShow\":1,\"categories\":[\"12\"],\"typeScale\":3,\"imageScale\":1,\"sectionHeader\":\"THAILAND\"} /-->\n\n<!-- wp:newspack-blocks/homepage-articles {\"className\":\"is-style-borders\",\"showExcerpt\":false,\"showImage\":false,\"showAuthor\":false,\"showAvatar\":false,\"mediaPosition\":\"left\",\"categories\":[\"12\"],\"typeScale\":1,\"imageScale\":1} /--></div>\n<!-- /wp:column -->\n\n<!-- wp:column -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\"><!-- wp:newspack-blocks/homepage-articles {\"className\":\"is-style-borders\",\"showExcerpt\":false,\"showAvatar\":false,\"postsToShow\":1,\"categories\":[\"13\"],\"typeScale\":3,\"imageScale\":1,\"mobileStack\":true,\"sectionHeader\":\"VIETNAM\"} /-->\n\n<!-- wp:newspack-blocks/homepage-articles {\"className\":\"is-style-borders\",\"showExcerpt\":false,\"showImage\":false,\"showAuthor\":false,\"showAvatar\":false,\"mediaPosition\":\"left\",\"categories\":[\"13\"],\"typeScale\":1,\"imageScale\":1} /--></div>\n<!-- /wp:column --></div>\n<!-- /wp:columns --></div></div>\n<!-- /wp:group -->\n\n<!-- wp:group -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-group\"><div class=\"wp-block-group__inner-container\"><!-- wp:columns -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-columns\"><!-- wp:column -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:column -->\n\n<!-- wp:column -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:column -->\n\n<!-- wp:column -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:column --></div>\n<!-- /wp:columns --></div></div>\n<!-- /wp:group -->','Homepage','','inherit','closed','closed','','7-revision-v1','','','2020-06-30 13:11:36','2020-06-30 16:11:36','',7,'http://localhost/index.php/2020/06/30/7-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(234,1,'2020-06-30 13:13:52','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','Rascunho automático','','auto-draft','open','open','','','','','2020-06-30 13:13:52','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://localhost/?p=234',0,'post','',0),(235,1,'2020-06-30 13:25:10','2020-06-30 16:25:10','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 2000, when the project was initially taken up by Myanmar, Thailand and Laos with Chinese financing, Thai&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.worldwatch.org/system/files/EP166B.pdf\">communities along this route expressed outrage</a>. The habitats impacted support hundreds of fish and other aquatic species, which they rely on for food and income. Decline in catches and river bank agriculture and increased flooding was already noticeable in 2003, when the first phase was nearly complete, yet the Thai government suspended blasting due to a border dispute with Laos.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>But China still wants&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.worldwatch.org/node/542\">a navigable shipping lane</a>&nbsp;extending 886 km between its Yunnan province to Luang Prabang in Laos. Presently, several sections along the route still&nbsp;allow only long, slim boats carrying just 60 tons to be piloted through their rocky outcrops and turbulent whirlpools. The objective, however, is for barges carrying 500 tons tethered in trains to glide along a placid, engineered channel like a&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.icwa.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/MZW-12.pdf\">Danube of the East</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Notwithstanding the romance some may attribute to such a transformation, its realization could be akin to genocide of an often overlooked but crucial wildlife population: birds.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Many riverine bird populations are under threat in the Mekong region and across the world, says leading ornithologist Philip Round, Associate Professor of Biology at Mahidol University. “The Mekong will be forced to sacrifice biodiversity on a scale the Danube never had, and humanity is increasingly realizing&nbsp;<a href=\"http://science.sciencemag.org/content/353/6296/288\">it should be fighting to hold onto</a>.”</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','The Bird’s Eye View: What Endangered Birds Tell Us About the Risks of Mekong Development','','publish','open','open','','the-birds-eye-view-what-endangered-birds-tell-us-about-the-risks-of-mekong-development','','','2020-06-30 13:25:42','2020-06-30 16:25:42','',0,'http://localhost/?p=235',0,'post','',0),(236,1,'2020-06-30 13:24:39','2020-06-30 16:24:39','É uma ave voando contente e livre','special-content','','inherit','open','closed','','special-content','','','2020-06-30 13:25:07','2020-06-30 16:25:07','',235,'http://localhost/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/special-content.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(237,1,'2020-06-30 13:25:10','2020-06-30 16:25:10','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 2000, when the project was initially taken up by Myanmar, Thailand and Laos with Chinese financing, Thai&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.worldwatch.org/system/files/EP166B.pdf\">communities along this route expressed outrage</a>. The habitats impacted support hundreds of fish and other aquatic species, which they rely on for food and income. Decline in catches and river bank agriculture and increased flooding was already noticeable in 2003, when the first phase was nearly complete, yet the Thai government suspended blasting due to a border dispute with Laos.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>But China still wants&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.worldwatch.org/node/542\">a navigable shipping lane</a>&nbsp;extending 886 km between its Yunnan province to Luang Prabang in Laos. Presently, several sections along the route still&nbsp;allow only long, slim boats carrying just 60 tons to be piloted through their rocky outcrops and turbulent whirlpools. The objective, however, is for barges carrying 500 tons tethered in trains to glide along a placid, engineered channel like a&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.icwa.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/MZW-12.pdf\">Danube of the East</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Notwithstanding the romance some may attribute to such a transformation, its realization could be akin to genocide of an often overlooked but crucial wildlife population: birds.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Many riverine bird populations are under threat in the Mekong region and across the world, says leading ornithologist Philip Round, Associate Professor of Biology at Mahidol University. “The Mekong will be forced to sacrifice biodiversity on a scale the Danube never had, and humanity is increasingly realizing&nbsp;<a href=\"http://science.sciencemag.org/content/353/6296/288\">it should be fighting to hold onto</a>.”</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','The Bird’s Eye View: What Endangered Birds Tell Us About the Risks of Mekong Development','','inherit','closed','closed','','235-revision-v1','','','2020-06-30 13:25:10','2020-06-30 16:25:10','',235,'http://localhost/index.php/2020/06/30/235-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(238,1,'2020-06-30 13:26:34','2020-06-30 16:26:34','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As darkness fell in the forests of central Myanmar on a rainy evening last July, May Thu and her husband Myint Swe*, were wrapping up their day’s work: illegal logging. May Thu, a petite 27-year-old with long black hair and shining black eyes, clambered on top of some logs assembled in a pile. It was monsoon season and the wood was slippery. She fell and landed on the buzzing blade of her husband’s chain saw.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>At first, there was no pain, but she knew she was in trouble.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>“OK, I just got injured by a chain saw, this will be big,” she recalls thinking.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Myint Swe, a gentle man with foxlike features and a nervous disposition, scooped her up.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>“It’s just a small one,” he lied as he carried her back to their village. They had been happily married for 10 years. But when she asked him to stop so she could look at the wound, she saw a deep incision across the backs of her legs, backside and vagina. There was a tremendous amount of blood.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>May Thu and Myint Swe live in a tiny village north of Mandalay, the country’s second largest city; a two-hour drive along bumpy roads plied by minivans and trucks, some carrying cut logs on their roofs. Their logging work is illegal.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The country has the third highest deforestation rate in the world, close behind Brazil and Indonesia, the worst offenders according to the UN Food and Agricultural Organization’s 2015<a href=\"http://www.fao.org/3/a-i4793e.pdf\">&nbsp;Global Forest Resources Assessment</a>. Between 2010 and 2015, the country lost a half a million hectares of forest annually. The government, led by Aung San Suu Kyi, has tried to slow the losses, introducing a ban on logging shortly after it came to power in 2016. It’s set to expire in April this year. Currently, the country’s timber needs are supposed to be served by stockpiles gathered by the state-run&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.myanmatimber.com.mm/\">Myanmar Timber Enterprise</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Chain Saw Injuries in Myanmar Tied to Illegal Logging','','publish','open','open','','chain-saw-injuries-in-myanmar-tied-to-illegal-logging','','','2020-06-30 13:26:43','2020-06-30 16:26:43','',0,'http://localhost/?p=238',0,'post','',0),(239,1,'2020-06-30 13:26:13','2020-06-30 16:26:13','Logs in transit by train on the Mandalay to Myitkyina line','special-content2','','inherit','open','closed','','special-content2','','','2020-06-30 13:26:34','2020-06-30 16:26:34','',238,'http://localhost/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/